  "statement": {
    "ambiguity_status": "minor",
    "intended": "Let $n\\geq 2$ and $\\pi(n)<k\\leq n$. Let $f(k,n)$ be the smallest integer $r$ such that in any $A\\subseteq \\{1,\\ldots,n\\}$ of size $\\lvert A\\rvert=k$ there exist primes $p_1,\\ldots,p_r$ such that $>r$ many $a\\in A$ are only divisible by primes from $\\{p_1,\\ldots,p_r\\}$. \n\nIs it true that\\[2\\pi(n^{1/2})-f(\\pi(n)+1,n)\\to \\infty\\]as $n\\to \\infty$?\n\nIn general, estimate $f(k,n)$, particularly when $\\pi(n)+1<k=o(n)$.",
